Ok, here's my attempt at the facts.

It took me two days to read this over again because I've been
documenting and classifying stuff as I went.  My most detailed notes
were ALL mentions of Snape that had anything to do with thoughts,
feelings, actions etc.  One or two only pages I left out where it just
mentioned he passed in the hall or something (nothing relevant to
annotate).  So everywhere Snape is mentioned is here and in the next
post.

So while doing so, I had five categories on my notepad.

1) EVIDENCE OF SNAPE'S EVIL DOINGS (To Harry et al)
2) EVIDENCE OF SNAPE'S HUMANITARIANISM
3) EVIDENCE OF FAIRNESS
4) EVIDENCE OF UNFAIRNESS
5) MISCELLANEOUS/WRONG EVIDENCE THAT SNAPE IS EVIL

Please Bear with me but this will be long and worth the read!  You
will see and weigh out where 95% at least of Snape's evilness is
nothing but a facade.  The proof is here (EVERY incident, no matter
how innocuous, I've included it).  with that said, here goes:
Please bear in mind as well:
By evil doings, I mean something that would endanger someone, kill
someone, be disloyal or illegal etc.
By Humanitarianism, I mean help, save or show compassion to someone
By fairness I mean how he's treating someone in compared to others and
By unfairness there is no obvious reason shown for him being mean or
unfair

I'll talk about the last and most interesting category in the next
post.

1) EVIDENCE OF SNAPE'S EVIL DOINGS
NOTHING.  There is not one reference in the book that Snape does
anything to harm anyone, kill anyone or even remotely put them in
jeopardy.  He's not pleasant, but nothing is shown for him to do
anything wrong that would hold up in a legal or moral court of law
either in a criminal or civil suit. I bow to anyone who PROVES it by
annotation from the book.

2) EVIDENCE OF SNAPE'S HUMANITARISM
a) P 139 Snape orders Neville to hospital wing after he melts
cauldron and boils on his nose.  (some people may argue he has to
because he's a teach so this may cancel itself out)
b) P 190 Snape is counter cursing (we later find out) Harry's
broom (Quidditch match) and on Page 289 Quirrell admits he was doing
the counter curse. He does this to save Harry.
c) P 289 It's revealed by Quirrell that Snape wanted to be
referee for the Quidditch match to protect Harry

3) EVIDENCE OF SNAPE'S FAIRNESS
a) P 136-138 Snape calls on him in class and he doesn't know the
answers.  Snape seems to be picking on him in Harry's view so Harry
quickly answers sarcastically &quot;I don't know sir, but I think Hermione
does&quot; &quot;Why don't you ask her&quot;.  Snape minus 1 point for &quot;cheek&quot;  ONE
point?  It's later revealed by Ron he takes lots of points from Fred
and George etc.  In my view this is fair and Harry was sarcastic.  I'd
of given Harry more than 1 point.  He WAS cheeky. Actually on the
subject of points from houses and points from Gryffindor, go back
through the book and total the number of points deducted from
Gryffindor from other professors.... it's MUCH less than Snape!
b) P 196 Malfoy insults Ron's family and Ron takes a swing at
Malfoy as Snape walks in.  Snape takes 5 points from Gryffindor for
fighting. He doesn't know what happened; it's right that he saw Ron
hitting someone and punished him; fighting actually deserves MORE than
5 points?  Detention perhaps or a letter home?
c) P 300 It is revealed that Snape detested James mostly for
saving his life; and he worked hard (Snape) all year to protect Harry
to return the favor (agreed selfish in a way because he wanted to feel
free of the burden of a debt owed) He's selfish, but he's being fair
in some sense; trying to even the score to his disadvantage; after
all, James is dead so this shows he's got some conscience.

4) EVIDENCE OF SNAPES UNFAIRNESS
a) P 139 Snape chastises Harry for standing next to Neville and
not helping him with the potion that landed him in the hospital and
deducts another point from Gryffindor. (actually this is justified
maybe; I mean he's possibly trying to teach the kids to help one
another here; so could actually go to the FAIR side, but I felt more
people would argue against this so I included it as being unfair)
b) P  182 Snape takes 5 points from Harry for having a library
book (Quidditch throughout the Ages) outside the school; which Ron
feels is a rule he made up (no proof of that; assumption and if an
actual rule, it again could go into the FAIR column but I knew people
would be whining so I put it here for the Snape nayers)
c) P 223 Snape awards Hufflepuff a penalty shot  because Fred and
George hit someone with a bludger and another penalty for no reason (
this is Harry's assessment which is clouded when it comes to Snape -
we can't be sure they didn't actually commit a foul so this could go
into the FAIR column as well)

So points so far.  BAD side
FACTUAL evidence Snape meant to harm/kill anyone in any way 0.
POSSIBLE evidence Snape meant to harm/kill anyone in any way 0
FACTUAL evidence that Snape was UNFAIR to the students in any way 0
POSSIBLE evidence Snape was unfair to Harry et al  3

So points so far GOOD side
FACTUAL evidence Snape showed some Humanitarianism 2
POSSIBLE evidence he showed Humanitarianism 1 (Neville to hospital)
FACTUAL evidence Snape FAIR 0
POSSIBLE Evidence he was fair 3

So  to the good side: Score 2 and 4 Possibles
So to the bad side: Score: 0 and 3 Possibles

the good side: Two HUGE Humanitarianism shows and 0 on the major
points where he's NOT nice in some way.  and 6-3 to the good side for
possibles.

This is just after Sorcerer's Stone.  What is your belief now?  Has it
changed any?  My guess is no.  People are solidified NO MATTER THE
EVIDENCE.

I will post the last thing in another post. I am quite anxious to see
what you say after this post and next.
