IMHO, what you´re both missing is the very fact that makes Snape
interesting: he´s one of the few, or maybe even the only,
tridimensional character in the books. You´re trying to classify him
in good or bad, hero or evil, when there´s much more to Snape than
just that.

Again just my opinion, the reason he´s mean in small, unimportant
things like house points is that it serves as a relief valve for the
highly stressful double-agent job he´s got himself into. As Voldemort
returns, this stress mounts, so it´s pretty consistent that he does no
great harm to the students is PS/SS, COS and PoA, but starts to get
more snappy from GoF on.

Another duality regards just Harry: he sees him first as James´ son,
so tends to give vent to his frustrations when in class (or in the
Occlumency sessions.) However, in life-threatening situations, his
love for Lily´s son comes first and he protects him.

That he isn´t the most adequate Potions teacher around is easily
acceptable; Trelawney is no academic wonder herself. Both ended up
teaching in Hogwarts, protected by DD, mainly due their position
regarding LV, not because of their skill in handling the students.
